Note:
Runtime atomic-operations API — the public lock-free synchronization surface
for the Runa runtime concurrency system.

This is the runtime-facing object layer. The actual atomic machinery is the
completed C11/C++11 typed-atomics facade in the primitives layer
(compiler/frontend/primitives/concurrency/atomic.runa), which itself dispatches
to the per-architecture ordered atomic instructions (LOCK XADD / LOCK CMPXCHG /
XCHG on x86_64, LL/SC loops on weakly ordered targets). This module does NOT
re-implement any atomic primitive; it provides runtime-named entry points that
delegate to the facade while preserving the C11 memory-ordering contract exactly
as the facade exposes it.

The reason for a dedicated runtime layer is the same as for the runtime mutex
object: runtime callers should program against one stable, runtime-namespaced
contract and the runtime-standard memory-ordering constants, rather than reaching
directly into the primitives tree. Every entry point here forwards its arguments
verbatim — including the memory-ordering parameter(s) — so the lock-free
semantics are identical to the facade with no loss of expressiveness.

Atomic handle model:
    A constructor returns an opaque non-zero Integer handle to a heap-owned
    atomic cell, or 0 on allocation failure. Every operation takes that handle
    as its first argument. A 0 handle is treated as a null object: reads and
    read-modify-write operations return 0, stores/frees report failure (0), and
    compare-and-swap reports failure (0) — none of them dereference the handle.

Memory ordering codes (C11 std::memory_order — values mirror the facade):
    ORDER_RELAXED = 0
    ORDER_ACQUIRE = 1
    ORDER_RELEASE = 2
    ORDER_ACQ_REL = 3
    ORDER_SEQ_CST = 4
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/concurrency/atomic.runa" as Atomic

Note: Memory ordering constants — re-exported from the primitives facade so
Note: runtime callers do not reach into the primitive layer. Values are byte
Note: identical to the C11 std::memory_order codes used throughout the facade.
Constant ORDER_RELAXED as Integer is 0
Constant ORDER_ACQUIRE as Integer is 1
Constant ORDER_RELEASE as Integer is 2
Constant ORDER_ACQ_REL as Integer is 3
Constant ORDER_SEQ_CST as Integer is 4

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Construction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "atomic_new_int64" takes initial_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a signed 64-bit atomic cell seeded with initial_value. The cell and
    its width-aware semantics come entirely from the primitives facade; this
    layer only exposes a runtime-named entry point.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to the facade atomic_int64_create, which allocates the 16-byte cell,
    tags it Int64, and publishes the initial value with a seq_cst store. The
    facade already returns 0 on allocation failure, which we propagate unchanged.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation plus one seq_cst store inside the facade. Cold path: done once
    per atomic cell.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 (NULL) on allocation failure; callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc atomic_int64_create from Atomic with initial_value
End Process

Process called "atomic_new_int32" takes initial_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a signed 32-bit atomic cell seeded with initial_value. Signed-narrow
    sign extension on load is handled by the facade's type code.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to the facade atomic_int32_create. The facade tags the cell Int32 so
    loads sign-extend the 32-bit word. Propagate 0 on allocation failure.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation plus one seq_cst store inside the facade.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 (NULL) on allocation failure; callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc atomic_int32_create from Atomic with initial_value
End Process

Process called "atomic_new_uint64" takes initial_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create an unsigned 64-bit atomic cell seeded with initial_value.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to the facade atomic_uint64_create, which tags the cell UInt64.
    Propagate 0 on allocation failure.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation plus one seq_cst store inside the facade.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 (NULL) on allocation failure; callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc atomic_uint64_create from Atomic with initial_value
End Process

Process called "atomic_new_uint32" takes initial_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create an unsigned 32-bit atomic cell seeded with initial_value. Loads are
    masked to the 0..2^32-1 range by the facade.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to the facade atomic_uint32_create, which tags the cell UInt32.
    Propagate 0 on allocation failure.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation plus one seq_cst store inside the facade.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 (NULL) on allocation failure; callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc atomic_uint32_create from Atomic with initial_value
End Process

Process called "atomic_new_bool" takes initial_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a boolean atomic cell. Any non-zero seed normalizes to 1; zero stays
    0. The normalization is performed by the facade.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to the facade atomic_bool_create, which tags the cell Bool and
    coerces the seed to 0 or 1. Propagate 0 on allocation failure.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation plus one seq_cst store inside the facade.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 (NULL) on allocation failure; callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc atomic_bool_create from Atomic with initial_value
End Process

Process called "atomic_new_pointer" takes initial_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a 64-bit pointer-width atomic cell seeded with initial_ptr, for
    lock-free pointer swaps and CAS-based data-structure roots.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to the facade atomic_pointer_create, which tags the cell Pointer and
    stores the 64-bit value verbatim. Propagate 0 on allocation failure.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation plus one seq_cst store inside the facade.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 (NULL) on allocation failure; callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc atomic_pointer_create from Atomic with initial_ptr
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Load / Store
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "atomic_read" takes a as Integer, order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically read the cell under the requested memory ordering, returning the
    type-correct value (signed narrows are sign-extended by the facade).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle and the ordering to the facade atomic_load, which selects
    the ordered load instruction and applies type masking. The ordering argument
    is passed through unchanged.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Relaxed reads are cheapest; acquire/seq_cst add fence cost on weakly ordered
    architectures (ARM / RISC-V / PowerPC).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 without dereferencing. The returned value is a
    transient read whose freshness is only guaranteed at the moment of the load.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_load from Atomic with a, order
End Process

Process called "atomic_write" takes a as Integer, value as Integer, order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically publish a new value into the cell under the requested memory
    ordering.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle, value, and ordering to the facade atomic_store, which
    masks the value to the cell's type and selects the ordered store instruction.
    The ordering argument is passed through unchanged.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Relaxed stores are cheapest; release/seq_cst add fence cost on weakly ordered
    architectures.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 (failure) without dereferencing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_store from Atomic with a, value, order
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Read-modify-write — each returns the PREVIOUS value
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "atomic_add" takes a as Integer, delta as Integer, order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically add delta to the cell and return the value held BEFORE the add,
    matching the C11 fetch_add contract.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle, delta, and ordering to the facade atomic_fetch_add, which
    performs the ordered RMW and returns the type-masked previous value.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    On x86 this is a LOCK XADD; on ARM / RISC-V it is an LL/SC loop.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 without dereferencing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with a, delta, order
End Process

Process called "atomic_sub" takes a as Integer, delta as Integer, order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically subtract delta from the cell and return the value held BEFORE the
    subtraction.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle, delta, and ordering to the facade atomic_fetch_sub, which
    performs the ordered RMW and returns the type-masked previous value.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    On x86 this is a NEG followed by LOCK XADD; on ARM / RISC-V it is an LL/SC
    loop.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 without dereferencing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_fetch_sub from Atomic with a, delta, order
End Process

Process called "atomic_and" takes a as Integer, mask as Integer, order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically bitwise-AND the cell with mask and return the value held BEFORE
    the operation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle, mask, and ordering to the facade atomic_fetch_and, which
    performs the ordered RMW and returns the type-masked previous value.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Lowered to a LOCK CMPXCHG retry loop on x86 and an LL/SC loop on weak archs.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 without dereferencing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_fetch_and from Atomic with a, mask, order
End Process

Process called "atomic_or" takes a as Integer, mask as Integer, order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically bitwise-OR the cell with mask and return the value held BEFORE the
    operation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle, mask, and ordering to the facade atomic_fetch_or, which
    performs the ordered RMW and returns the type-masked previous value.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Lowered to a LOCK CMPXCHG retry loop on x86 and an LL/SC loop on weak archs.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 without dereferencing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_fetch_or from Atomic with a, mask, order
End Process

Process called "atomic_xor" takes a as Integer, mask as Integer, order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically bitwise-XOR the cell with mask and return the value held BEFORE
    the operation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle, mask, and ordering to the facade atomic_fetch_xor, which
    performs the ordered RMW and returns the type-masked previous value.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Lowered to a LOCK CMPXCHG retry loop on x86 and an LL/SC loop on weak archs.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 without dereferencing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_fetch_xor from Atomic with a, mask, order
End Process

Process called "atomic_swap" takes a as Integer, value as Integer, order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically store value into the cell and return the value held BEFORE the
    exchange, matching the C11 exchange contract.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle, value, and ordering to the facade atomic_exchange, which
    masks the new value to the cell's type, performs the ordered swap, and returns
    the type-masked previous value.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    On x86 XCHG carries an implicit LOCK prefix (a full barrier); on ARM / RISC-V
    it is an LL/SC loop.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 without dereferencing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_exchange from Atomic with a, value, order
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Compare-and-swap
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "atomic_compare_and_swap" takes a as Integer, expected as Integer, desired as Integer, success_order as Integer, failure_order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Strong compare-and-swap: atomically replace the cell with desired only if it
    currently equals expected. Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure. The strong
    form never spuriously fails, so a single attempt is authoritative.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle, expected, desired, and BOTH the success and failure
    memory orderings to the facade atomic_compare_exchange, which type-masks the
    operands, normalizes the orderings per the C11 compare-exchange rules, and
    performs the strong CAS. All five arguments are passed through unchanged.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    CAS is the most expensive single atomic op; design lock-free algorithms to
    minimize the CAS rate.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 (failure) without dereferencing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_compare_exchange from Atomic with a, expected, desired, success_order, failure_order
End Process

Process called "atomic_compare_and_swap_weak" takes a as Integer, expected as Integer, desired as Integer, success_order as Integer, failure_order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Weak compare-and-swap: same semantics as the strong form but permitted to
    fail spuriously on architectures with LL/SC, so it must be used inside a retry
    loop. It is cheaper on those targets because no inner retry is required.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle, expected, desired, and BOTH the success and failure
    memory orderings to the facade atomic_compare_exchange_weak, which type-masks
    the operands, normalizes the orderings per the C11 compare-exchange rules, and
    performs the weak CAS. All five arguments are passed through unchanged.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Prefer the weak form in CAS retry loops on weakly ordered architectures; on
    x86 it lowers to the same LOCK CMPXCHG as the strong form.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 (failure) without dereferencing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_compare_exchange_weak from Atomic with a, expected, desired, success_order, failure_order
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Fences and teardown
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "atomic_thread_fence" takes order as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Standalone memory fence: establish a happens-before barrier of the requested
    strength without touching any specific atomic cell, for algorithms that pair
    relaxed atomics with explicit fences.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the ordering to the facade atomic_fence, which emits the matching
    acquire / release / acq_rel / seq_cst barrier. The ordering argument is passed
    through unchanged; no handle is involved.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    On x86 only seq_cst requires a real instruction (MFENCE); acquire/release are
    compiler barriers under TSO. On weak archs each maps to the matching DMB.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure ordering construct; touches no memory.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc atomic_fence from Atomic with order
End Process

Process called "atomic_free" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release a heap-owned atomic cell. Must be called exactly once per cell, after
    all threads have stopped using it.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forward the handle to the facade atomic_destroy, which deallocates the cell
    and returns 1 on success. The facade already treats a 0 handle as a no-op
    returning 0, and we guard it here as well so no dereference is attempted.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One deallocation inside the facade. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null handle returns 0 (failure) without dereferencing. Freeing a cell still in
    use by another thread is a logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc atomic_destroy from Atomic with a
End Process
